<br>
Also, I don't really see a need for you to make personal attacks on me. I have no control issues, and if I need help, it's because I spend way too much damn time on a computer. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I feel like I should say this, yet again: I never said anything about whether or not drugs should be legal, just that they are not victimless. Believe it or not, I agree with you more than you think - I'm well aware that sending people to jail for marijuana consumption is generally a very bad decision. I think that most of the people that use marijuana use it casually, and do not hurt anyone else. By putting them in jail, you simply ruin their future, therefore making them more likely to commit crimes because they cannot support themselves financially.<br>
<br>
I'm aware that there would be less gang violence and drug wars if police did not need to enforce drug laws. The legalization of drugs would obviously reduce the deaths in that area of law enforcement.<br>
<br>
Point Number Two: I have an understanding of freedom. I realize that I am free to say what I'm saying on this board. The open discussion of ideas is, I feel, the key point of freedom. <br>
<br>
And finally, regarding the freedom issue, it's not a black and white subject. If I was free to do what I wanted to do, that may mean that I would impede on other's freedoms. If other people were free to do whatever they wanted to do, I would probably suffer some encumbrance to do what I wanted to do. I think this topic goes deeper than the human brain is capable of delving through, and has so many tangents that it's really impossible to discuss in one, coherent thread.<br>
<br>
I like to think that what differs man from animals is our free will, and our ability to logically think things through. However, I've also seen studies saying that love might be nothing more than a chemical reaction.<br>
<br>
On one hand, there is complete and total self control and free will; the proactive, romantic ideology that defines what a lot of people feel is freedom, and on the other, there's the reactive, naturalist point of view, where man is really no more than an animal, and simply responds to what it is presented with, without individual thought. There are also thousands of degrees in opinion inbetween the two.<br>
<br>
I have no clue which one I hold on to, but I know this: there is nothing a person could do that will not affect others in some way. It may be very subtle and minute, it may be catostrophic. I feel that as a society, it is our responsibility to look out for one another, while not trampling upon natural freedoms. It's all a compromise. I don't want someone running my life, however I don't really feel like I'd make it very far if I didn't have some help from time to time. I'm done with this discussion, and quite frankly, I had fun. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br>
<br>
